Extract text, tables, images, and metadata from a document. Same behaviour as the bare-file invocation; kept as an explicit subcommand for scripts that prefer unambiguous CLI shapes

Usage: udoc extract [OPTIONS] [FILES]...

Arguments:
  [FILES]...
          Document path(s). Use - for stdin. Multiple files for batch extraction

Options:
  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

Output mode:
  -O, --out <MODE>
          Output mode (text|json|jsonl|tsv|markdown|chunks). Default `text`

          Possible values:
          - text:     Plain text (default)
          - json:     Full document JSON
          - jsonl:    Streaming JSON Lines, one record per page
          - tsv:      Tables only, tab-separated values
          - markdown: LLM-friendly markdown with citation anchors
          - chunks:   Chunked NDJSON for ingest pipelines (requires `--chunk-by`)

      --chunk-by <STRATEGY>
          Chunk strategy when `--out chunks` (page|heading|section|size)

          Possible values:
          - page:    One chunk per page
          - heading: One chunk per Block::Heading boundary
          - section: One chunk per top-level (rank-1) heading boundary
          - size:    Target N chars per chunk; never split a paragraph

      --chunk-size <CHUNK_SIZE>
          Chunk size in chars when `--chunk-by size` (default 2000)
          
          [default: 2000]

Filter:
  -p, --pages <PAGES>
          Page range (e.g., "1-5", "3,7,9-12")

  -F, --input-format <INPUT_FORMAT>
          Force input format (pdf, docx, xlsx, pptx, doc, xls, ppt, odt, ods, odp, rtf, md). Renamed from `--format` to disambiguate from `--out`

      --password <PASSWORD>
          Document password (encrypted PDF)

Hooks:
      --ocr <OCR>
          OCR hook command

      --hook <HOOK>
          Post-processing hook (repeatable)

      --ocr-all
          OCR all pages, not just textless ones

      --hook-image-dir <HOOK_IMAGE_DIR>
          Directory for page images passed to hooks

      --hook-timeout <HOOK_TIMEOUT>
          Per-page hook timeout in seconds (default: 60)

Resource limits:
      --max-file-size <MAX_FILE_SIZE>
          Maximum file size (e.g., "256mb", "1gb", "4096")

      --max-pages <MAX_PAGES>
          Maximum pages/sheets/slides to extract

      --no-tables
          Skip table detection (PDF only, ~16% faster)

      --no-images
          Skip image extraction (PDF only, ~19% faster). Disables in-parser image decoding entirely. Use `udoc images <file>` (subcommand) when you want to dump embedded images

Output formatting:
      --no-presentation
          Omit presentation overlay from JSON/JSONL

      --raw-spans
          Include raw positioned spans in JSON output

      --pretty
          Pretty-print JSON output

  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output file (default: stdout)

      --image-dir <IMAGE_DIR>
          Output directory for `--out chunks` images / `images` subcommand dumps (default: current directory)

      --errors <FORMAT>
          Error output format on stderr: `human` (default) or `json`. The JSON form emits one object per line (`{"code","message","context"}`) so agents grep-ing under `2>&1` can recover the structured error without parsing the human prose. The error-code strings are part of the agent contract

          Possible values:
          - human: Human-readable lines: `udoc: <message>`. Default
          - json:  One JSON object per line on stderr: `{"code":"E_FORMAT_UNSUPPORTED","message":"...","context":"..."}`
          
          [default: human]

Misc:
  -q, --quiet
          No-op kept for backwards compatibility. udoc is silent on stderr by default; `--quiet` is implicit. Pass `-v` to opt back in

  -v, --verbose...
          Show diagnostic warnings on stderr. Pass `-v` once for warnings (font fallbacks, recovered xref, table-detection skips), `-vv` for warnings + info-level progress (per-font ToUnicode loads, per-page reading-order tier). Repeated identical messages are deduplicated

      --jobs <JOBS>
          Number of parallel in-process extraction threads.
          
          Throughput peaks around `--jobs 16` on this codebase (P06 finding). Past that, in-process parallelism loses to cache and memory- bandwidth contention -- not the allocator (P07 verified mimalloc makes it worse). For larger fan-out use `--processes` instead. Mutually exclusive with `--processes`.
          
          [default: 1]

      --processes <PROCESSES>
          Number of subprocess workers for batch extraction.
          
          Spawns N child `udoc` processes via fork+exec; each child processes a disjoint slice of the input files. The kernel reclaims every page when each child exits, so this is the canonical pattern for very-large-corpus batches that otherwise hit the in-process scaling cliff. Mutually exclusive with `--jobs`.
